nExample 3:\n\nInput: nums = [1,3,2]\nOutput: false\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= nums.length <= 105\n-105 <= nums[i] <= 105\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def isMonotonic(self, nums: List[int]) -> bool:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def isMonotonic(self, nums: List[int]) -> bool:\n        if not nums:\n            return True\n        \n        increasing = decreasing = True\n        \n        for i in range(1, len(nums)):\n            if nums[i] > nums[i - 1]:\n                decreasing = False\n            if nums[i] < nums[i - 1]:\n                increasing = False\n        \n        return increasing or decreasing\n```\n\nThis solution checks if the array is either entirely non-increasing or non-decreasing. It iterates through the array once, comparing each element with the previous one to determine if the sequence is breaking the increasing or decreasing property. If the array is either entirely non-increasing or non-decreasing, it returns `True`; otherwise, it returns `False`.", "estimated_date": 1535846400000}